\begin_layout Section
Verb conjugation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mawacin's verb conjugation system is rather divergent.
 Most saliently, the tense system is completely gone; instead, a larger,
 two-tier aspect system evolved partly from the old tense suffixes.
 The modality, voice, and nonfinite paradigms have been greatly expanded
 due to the grammaticalization of various periphrastic constructions.
 Here's an example of an extensively conjugated verb, with its constituent
 parts:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\underset{\text{root}}{\text{mawa}}\hspace{1em}\underset{\text{\scshape ipfv}}{\text{-sta}}\hspace{1em}\underset{\text{\scshape prf}}{\text{-nda}}\hspace{1em}\underset{\text{\scshape des}}{\text{-ntȯ}}\hspace{1em}\underset{\text{\scshape inch}}{\text{-ka}}\hspace{1em}\underset{\text{\scshape adv}}{\text{-toc}}\\
\text{`starting to wish to have been talking'}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Verbs conjugate for 
\series bold
aspect
\series default
, 
\series bold
mood
\series default
, 
\series bold
voice
\series default
, and can head non-verb phrases through 
\series bold
nonfinite
\series default
 conjugation.
 The following subsections will discuss each of these in detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aspect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aspect relates the time of an event to a reference point, or views the event
 in a particular way.
 The aspect marker must go before any nonfinite conjugations; multiple aspects
 may be stacked in the logical order if doing so makes sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
