\begin_layout Subsection
Non-finite conjugations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-finite conjugations convert a verb phrase into other types of phrases.
 Obviously, they go last, and cannot have finite conjugations attached to
 them, as the word is no longer a verb!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Converbs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Converbs are a type of non-finite conjugation that essentially creates adverbial
 phrases.
 However, they can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inherit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 arguments from the surrounding verb phrase by using placeholder oronouns
 or adverbs.
 For example, the pronoun that refers to the surrounding verb phrase's subject
 is 
\emph on
i
\emph default
, behaving like a Type III noun.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Provisional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The provisional converb establishes conditions for the main clause.
 It's formed by adding a suffix 
\emph on
-ngoc
\emph default
.
 Combined with the tentative mood, it implies a more hypothetical condition
 (compare Classical Japanese 
\emph on
-aba
\emph default
 vs 
\emph on
-eba
\emph default
) 
\end_layout

